05195nam a22005415i 9780226717487DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222011ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226717487  a(DE-B1597)626060  a(OCoLC)1312727429  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aMUS0000002bisacsh1 aRiesman, Bob, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aI Feel So Good :bThe Life and Times of Big Bill Broonzy /cBob Riesman. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2022] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b33 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tForeword -- tAppreciation -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- t1 Swing Low, Sweet Chariot -- t2 My Name Is William Lee Conley Broonzy -- t3 When Will I Get to Be Called a Man? -- t4 Let’s Go Away from Here! -- t5 “I’m Gonna Play This Guitar Tonight from A to Z!” -- t6 Serve It to Me Right -- t7 State Street Boys -- t8 Just a Dream -- t9 Big Bill and Josh Are Here to Play the Blues for You -- t10 Preachin’ the Blues -- t11 Blues at Midnight -- t12 “That’s the Nicest Guy I Ever Met in My Life” -- t13 Stranger in a Strange Land -- t14 Nourish Yourself on Big Bill -- t15 “Be Proud of What You Are!” -- t16 Too Many Isms -- t17 Low Light and Blue Smoke -- t18 “A Requiem for the Blues” -- tEpilogue -- tAfterword -- tSelected Discography -- tBill on Film -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA major figure in American blues and folk music, Big Bill Broonzy (1903–1958) left his Arkansas Delta home after World War I, headed north, and became the leading Chicago bluesman of the 1930s. His success came as he fused traditional rural blues with the electrified sound that was beginning to emerge in Chicago. This, however, was just one step in his remarkable journey: Big Bill was constantly reinventing himself, both in reality and in his retellings of it. Bob Riesman’s groundbreaking biography tells the compelling life story of a lost figure from the annals of music history. I Feel So Good traces Big Bill’s career from his rise as a nationally prominent blues star, including his historic 1938 appearance at Carnegie Hall, to his influential role in the post-World War II folk revival, when he sang about racial injustice alongside Pete Seeger and Studs Terkel. Riesman’s account brings the reader into the jazz clubs and concert halls of Europe, as Big Bill's overseas tours in the 1950s ignited the British blues-rock explosion of the 1960s. Interviews with Eric Clapton, Pete Townshend, and Ray Davies reveal Broonzy’s profound impact on the British rockers who would follow him and change the course of popular music. Along the way, Riesman details Big Bill’s complicated and poignant personal saga: he was married three times and became a father at the very end of his life to a child half a world away. He also brings to light Big Bill’s final years, when he first lost his voice, then his life, to cancer, just as his international reputation was reaching its peak. Featuring many rarely seen photos, I Feel So Good will be the definitive account of Big Bill Broonzy’s life and music.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican American musicians -- Biography. 0aAfrican American musicians. 0aBlues musicians -- United States -- Biography. 0aBroonzy, Big Bill, -- 1893-1958. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  abig bill broonzy, blues, folk music, arkansas, chicago, biography, musician, carnegie hall, studs terkel, pete seeger, race, politics, justice, equality, concert halls, jazz clubs, british blues-rock, european tour, ray davies, eric clapton, townshend, black musicians, fame, celebrity, cancer, marriage, family, behind t